shifting sands of cuban science 1870 1933 center for latin american studies jump to navigation stanford university center for latin american studies search this site home events shifting sands of cuban science 1870 1933 shifting sands of cuban science 1870 1933 tuesday march 13 2012 12 15pm 1 05pm cuba's cast of scientific actors remained surprisingly constant between the island's first war of independence and the end of the first cuban republic nevertheless the us occupation of 1898 1902 acted as a prism redistributing energies that had been overwhelmingly concentrated in medical research generating a greater but relatively dispersed range of research practices that did not cohere in a national scientific program the talk maps a large and original community of scientists over this crucial era in the making of modern cuba and pays particular attention to the shifting fortunes of key players in their relationship to political power the spanish colonial state prior to 1898 the us military government from 1898 1902 and the republican state from 1902 1933 steven palmer is an associate professor and canada research chair in history of international health at the university of windsor canada he is the author of from popular medicine to medical populism doctors healers and public power in costa rica 1800 1940 duke 2003 and launching global health the caribbean odyssey of the rockefeller foundation michigan 2010 and co editor with juanita de barros and david wright of medicine and health in the circum caribbean 1800 1968 routledge 2009 in 2010 he co edited with claudia agostoni a special issue of the canadian journal of latin american and caribbean studies landscapes of latin american health his current work focuses on the politics of cuban medical research in the late colonial and early republican period part of a larger project to map scientific collaboration in the national atlantic world between 1840 and the 1970s his article migrant clinics and hookworm science the peripheral origins of international health 1840 1920 appeared in the bulletin of the history of medicine 84 3 2009 beginnings of cuban bacteriology juan santos fernandez medical research and the search for scientific sovereignty appeared in the august 2011 number of the hispanic american historical review steven palmer associate professor and canada research chair in history of international health university of windsor canada bolivar house 582 alvarado row last updated january 25 2012 10 58am calendar main menu about degree programs visiting faculty & scholar programs grants & fellowships people events newsletter giving to clas secondary menu stanford home ica clasp login contact stanford university center for latin american studies bolivar house 582 alvarado row stanford ca 94305 usa phone 650.723 4444 fax 650.723 9822 stanford university terms of use copyright complaints
